accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select material restricted as noted, in accordance with the terms of donation from the Laurance S. Rockefeller estate. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Mary French Rockefeller papers are arranged in original order, as received in the following series:
Series 1: Women's Interests, and Civic, Educational, and Religious Interests Series 2: Personal papers and Family Interests Series 3: Art and Culture

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them, and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Mary French Rockefeller, philanthropist and wife of Laurance S. Rockefeller, spent her career promoting and advocating for leadership opportunities for women and girls. This collection of her papers documents her activities in civic, educational and religious organizations as well as her interests in culture and the ar

The collection primarily documents her decades of service to the Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA) and dedicated advocacy for women and girls throughout the world. Mary began her service to YWCA as a member of the national board in 1951, and became vice-chair of the International Division in 1955, continuing as either vice-chair or chair through 1973. In the late 1950s and early 1960s, she also served as chair of the YWCA's World Service Council, and was then elected to the Board of Trustees in 1988.

Mary French Rockefeller also hosted and/or planned and participated in many events and fundraising and development campaigns, as well as traveled extensively, often with Laurance S. Rockefeller, to study YWCA activities and programs, and promote the growth and development of women leaders, throughout the world

The collection also documents Mary French Rockefeller's activities as a committee member or trustee of the Foreign Policy Association, Gordon-Conwell Theological Seminary, New York Community Trust, Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, Spelman College, United Board for Christian Education in Asia, and the Whitney Museum of American Art.
Mary French Rockefeller's personal giving, and a selection of files from her giving program, are documented as well as a variety of Rockefeller family activities and events.
